            <biogHist>
                <p>Duncan Cameron was born c1818 in Morvern. As his name doesn't appear in this area
                    in the 1841 or 1851 censuses, it is possible that he was away on police service.
                    He may have been away in Westport, Co. Mayo, where his wife was born, but we
                    should note that she was living in Muckairn when they married in 1856.</p>
                <p>In 1856 Duncan Cameron (38), police constable, living in Strontian, son of
                    Alexander Cameron and Catherine Cameron (deceased) was married in the Parish of
                    Muckairn on 20 October to Mary Anne Leonard, 26. Mary Anne was living in Aird,
                    Muckairn and was the daughter of Laurence Leonard of the Inland Revenue and
                    Bridget Leonard née MacManus (deceased). The witnesses as noted on the
                    certificate were William MacPherson and John MacCallum.</p>
                <p>In 1886 Carmichael met Duncan Cameron on 7 August while in Lochaline. Later on
                    his trip would take him to Mull. He describes him as 'a man of great
                    intelligence and full of the old lore of the old Highland people.' He recorded a
                    blessing for newly woven clothes, 'Coisrigeadh an Aodaich', as well as possibly
                    a couple of charms. He may have visited him later at his house in Tobermory,
                    where he saw a couple of harvest maidens, maighdeannann-buana, on the wall.
                    Clearly Duncan Cameron must have acquired material in Tiree as well as from his
                    own family background.  </p>
                <p>Probably in the late 1860s Duncan Cameron, described as 'maor riaghailt an
                    Tiriodh', gave John Dewar part of the Fenian ballad Conn man an Deirg ['aireamh
                    beag de na roinn']: NLS Adv. MS 50.2.20 ff. 148-151.</p>
                <p>On 1 May 1871 the Rev. John Gregorson Campbell of Tiree wrote to John Francis
                    Campbell sending a copy of Cian mac an Luaimh, most of which was got from Duncan
                    Campbell: NLS Adv. MS 50.2.3 ff. 194-195.</p>
                <p>On 12 September 1871 John Francis Campbell met Duncan Cameron at Scarinish in
                    Tiree. Cameron sang The Lay of the Muireartach and An t-Amadan Mòr, both of
                    which he learnt from his mother, his grandmother, and old man John Mackinnon,
                    shoemaker in Mull about Freichadal, and from his grandfather, who lived in
                    Morvern 'whence all the people have been driven out'. He also gave Campbell the
                    traditional warning given at Glencoe before the massacre:'Faic m' eich-sa agus
                    t' eich fhéin.' Later on, before a bigger audience, Cameron sang The Song of the
                    Smithy [Laoidh na Ceàrdaich]; Luidh a' Choin Mhòir; Luidh Mhànuis; Sgial air
                    Conn Mac an Deirg [a-rithist]; a single stanza; and a Fairy Changeling's Charm.
                    He ended by giving Campbell a list of 31 poems he could sing: NLS Adv. MS 50.2.4
                    fos. 55-59.</p>
                <p>In 1900 Duncan Cameron, ex-constable, widower of Mary Ann Leonard, died 7 March at
                    0:45am at Argyll Terrace, Tobermory. He had suffered from senile debility for
                    several months and his son, Duncan Cameron, signed the certificate. </p>
                <p>In the second volume of Carmina Gadelica, published later that year, Alexander
                    Carmichael says 'Much traditional lore of great excellence died with this highly
                    intelligent lorist.' In Carmina, to Cameron are ascribed 'Coisrigeadh an
                    Aodaich' (blessing of newly woven clothes), 'Sian a Bheatha Bhaun' (protective
                    charm), and 'An Tuis' (The Incense). The 'Coisrigeadh', or another version of
                    it, is again printed in Carmina, vol. iv, pp. 96-97. In Carmina, vol. v, pp.
                    360-367, we have the story and song of 'Mairearad Bhòidheach', which he probably
                    picked up in the Ross of Mull.</p>
